longest_values: We have an extensive arts program at MS 50 that combines in-school arts curricula, provided by to itinerant Middle School Arts Matters teachers (visual arts and music, our Integrated Arts Program (IAP) that partners Community School teaching artists with content area teachers (ELA, Social Studies, ENL) to integrate theater, visual arts, music and dance into our content area curricula, diverse arts programming as part of our Expanded Learning Time (ELT), and an inter-disciplinary mural project. El Puente’s IAP includes a codified professional development/training curriculum to support teachers to work with teaching artists to create integrated lesson plans and theme-based projects that will enrich the math curriculum. MS 50 has also partnered wtih El Puente to engage its resident mural group, Los Muralistas de El Puente, to create community murals on MS50’s large exterior wall on Roebling St. as well as on several interior school walls. Los Muralistas will not just to create the mural for the school, but will facilitate an interdisciplinary mural painting initiative. Students will gather oral histories in social studies, design mural proposals in ELA, study scaling in math, and analyze effects of erosion on different paints/surfaces in science. Our community mural painting project, for example, will have an important math application as students will be asked to use transferring, graphing, and scaling to in bringing the mural from design to larger than life reality."

The PS/MS 57 Arts program includes visual, music, theater and dance components. All students receive arts enrichment in these areas. Prekindergarten has music, role-play, poetry and movement as integral components of everyday. K-8th grades infuse poetry, music & art into CCLS-based lessons which are developed by the teachers and instructional teams. In addition to embedded school-based visual arts instruction, we have an Arts partnership with the 92nd Street 'Y' that provides stimulating student experiences through choral training that culminates in a district-wide showcase with several participating schools. 92nd St. Y also engaged students in visual arts, Hip Hop and musical introduction. This year the 'Dancing in the Classrooms' served 5th grade and 'Ballroom Basics' company serves our middle school population. These dance programs culminate in the school's participation in a citywide competition. After-school programs such as the YMCA, Roads to Success, and City Year provide arts exposure via varied dance genres such as hip hop and tap; while the staff enhances support of the arts initiative via after-school chorus, flag corps, step squad and classical music appreciation for K-8th grade students."

Our school scope is to expose our students to the arts in order for them to find ways of expressing their feelings through integrating all the core subjects. Our school environment is such that all the arts are integrated, including a program after school entitled, Arts and Literacy. The arts engage students in a variety of modalities that enable them to achieve personal and corporate goals in music, visual art, dance, theater, and more. Our students have been exposed to many forms of art that aid in their achievement in core subjects such as literacy, math, social studies, science, and social skills. Thus far, our students have had the privilege of going on many class trips to museums, musical forums, theater and dance institutions which have expanded their experiences and personal vision. The art program at P.S. 877 has exposed students to many art forms, thus enabling them to grow in their personal, physical, mental, emotional and artistic development. Our vibrant arts curriculum plays a large part in our students becoming productive members of society and the global community surrounding them."

Our Arts program continues to allow students to develop creatively and challenge their knowledge of style, artists and cultural contributions to the world of the Arts. We support the individual talents that students posses in music performance, music theory and visual arts. We accomplish this through integration of curriculum across the content areas; we maintain high expectations through standards based education. Keeping with the common core standards math and literacy continue to play an important role. As students use skills in measurement, experimentation, reading comprehension, expand vocabulary and defending opinions through arguments while exposed to a variety of text, visual representations lead student discussion and dialogue as they acquire meaning. We prepare students during the middle school years to be armed with the tools and achievement expectation that will afford them successful paths in high school and college."

Given this focus, we have boosted our level of performance, and expanded both of our annual winter and spring concerts to encompass more diversity and theatrical elements. We also put together an elaborate production of the theatrical play, Antigone, with full cast and crew! We have also expanded on our International Day celebrations to include more performance opportunities that highlight a variety of cultures. In addition, we have created partnerships with local Arts Educational programs to prepare our students with the foundational skills needed to succeed in these realms. Through these comprehensive programs, students learn valuable, life-long skills that are necessary to working in large and diverse groups. Additionally, they broaden the scope of our school community, allowing for teachers, students and parents to come together and acknowledge the hard work and diligence found within our Performing and Visual Arts Program."

We are a limited non-screened community high school in a high-needs neighborhood (we are in District 16 in Bed Stuy Brooklyn and are a SWP Title I program).  Arts has been an essential ingredient of our school's mission and vision since we opened our doors in 2007.  We are also a member of the NY Performance Standards Consortium (the schools across NYS that have a regents waiver), which allows us to innovate performance based graduation tasks like our art requirement.  We firmly believe that our arts opportunities provide an essential engagement tool for our at-risk population.  We would highlight that our emphasis on the arts is woven into the fabric of our school and is vital to our identity and mission and success.  However, as a limited non-screened district community school, we do not receive any additional funding to support the arts, which means this extremely important aspect of our school community is something we have to fund entirely with regular school funds.  The grants we received last year do not contribute to the in-school arts instruction we provide all our students.  The principal teaches one art class each year to provide the necessary seats for our arts students, but that is not a sustainable long term plan.  As a school that can point to concrete benefits of having robust arts programming in a high-needs district, we hope to see increased funding for the arts as part of the City's commitment to equity in education.

"Please note that the data recorded in STARS does not reflect the entirety of our arts programming.  For example, third grade does not currently receive music instruction as a cluster period.  However, students participate in the Link Up program in conjunction with Carnegie Hall, whereby they enjoy intensive orchestral music education and learn to play the recorder.  They also participate in a community-oriented Flag Day ceremony which fuses theater, dance, and music - and is the centerpiece of our civic education as PS 6.  The aforementioned is done during the music teacher's administrative period, or when the classroom teachers have availability and is not termed as ""music"" within the tracking database.  Where programming does not suit our creative/compliance needs, we accommodate accordingly.   In that vein, the dance teacher has instituted a Dance Company.  Children engage in choreography/performance for festivals and events throughout the school year.  Similarly, the visual arts teacher has formed a stagecraft club; students create set pieces for the numerous productions that we stage at PS 6.  We are pleased to offer our students an extensive artistic menu to reflect their diverse interests and capabilities."

Our Arts program continues to allow students to develop creatively and challenge their knowledge of style, artists and cultural contributions to the world of the Arts. We support the individual talents that students posses in music performance, music theory and visual arts. We accomplish this through integration of curriculum across the content areas; we maintain high expectations through standards based education. Keeping with the common core standards math and literacy continue to play an important role. As students use skills in measurement, experimentation, reading comprehension, expand vocabulary and defending opinions through arguments while exposed to a variety of text, visual representations lead student discussion and dialogue as they acquire meaning. We prepare students during the middle school years to be armed with the tools and achievement expectation that will afford them successful paths in high school and college.

Our high school is a science oriented school. Our distinguishing feature is the field studies program that all incoming 9th graders take in tandem with the Living Environment class. We are partnered with the Brooklyn Botanic Garden, and within this partnership, students spend one afternoon every week in BBG or Prospect Park learning environmental science and biology, hands on, in the great outdoors. Most of our elective classes are geared towards environmental science and the sciences (sustainable agriculture, science research classes, AP Biology, etc.). As for our student body, our school is made up of mostly African-American students of Caribbean descent, with an additional small group of Southeast Asia and Sub-Saharan African students. We service a large percentage of students with IEPS and use an inclusion model of instruction partnering Special Education teachers with the content teachers in the same classroom.

School Community PS 4 K is a Special Education School with 366 students from Grade PreK through Grade 5. The school population comprises of 62.02 % Black, 25.68% Hispanic, 4.91 % White, 4.37% Asian, and 3.02 % others. Our Special Education PreK- Grade 5 student body includes 16.7 % ENL students , and 83.3% Special Education Students. The following populations of students with Autism Spectrum Disorders (ASD), and other varying behavioral and developmental impairments represent: 6:1:1 ; 12:1:1 ; and 8:1:1. Boys account for 72.40% of the students enrolled, and girls account for 27.59%, representing a ratio of about 3:1. The average attendance rate for the school year 2015-2016 was 89.30%. We pursue a rigorous CCLS-alighned Curriculum Map driven by the 3-E Instructional Model within a Center -based Interdisciplinary Learning Approach for all student to meet lifelong learning and independence

frequent_values: There are three components to Dos Puentes Arts program: visual art, music and dance. Visual art is provided by Studio in a School and serves all our students weekly. Children work with a teaching artist in Spanish to learn sculpture, drawing, painting, and printing. This is extended into the classroom during our daily Exploration period. Children also receive music weekly. They learn to sing, drum, and use other percussion instruments. Second graders learn ukulele and third graders learned recorder. There are at least two musical/ dance performances a year. We have a full-time dance teacher who serves all our students 2xs a week. Students learn creative movement, cultural dances and how to collaborate around a presentation in Spanish. As a dual language Spanish/English school, language and culture are reinforced through the arts both in the classroom and in these specialty areas. All classrooms also participate in our New Victory Theater partnership seeing performances at the midtown theater. We are also fortunate that are after school program provides other enrichment opportunities through Chorus, “Just Dance”, Latin Dance, Zumba, and Capoeira.

We have a certified Graphic arts program in our school. Additionally all 9th grade students take an art class. We offer dance, video making, and music production in after school programs through the 21st century grant

We are a small school, but intend to offer new programs to students. These will include guest speakers, continue clubs, school-wide projects and art competitions across grades. We will continue to develop arts exhibits, highlighting the best that our students can create. We will continue with our talent show as well. We also implemented several ceramics classes to engage diverse learners in the various functions of creating pottery and sculpture. Next school year we will starting a 3D printing program.

"Irwin Altman Middle School 172 is committed to providing our students with a quality arts education and assuring that we are following our mission to ""make this school the educational center of this community"" which is culturally and artistically diverse. The Blueprint for Teaching and Learning in the Arts has provided a guide for our curriculum development in visual arts, vocal and instrumental music and theatre production; similarly in Digital Film/ Computer Coding we have followed the Common Core 6-8 Literacy in Science and Technology Subjects Standards to supplement our curriculum focused on Computer Science for All and computer fluency for creating digital media products."

Public School 349 currently serves students in Pre-Kindergarten, Kindergarten, 1st grade and 2nd grade.  Providing music and visual arts is an important part of our curriculum. Our music program, in collaboration with “Music in Brain”, is inspired by scientific and neurological research linking music and cognitive development. Music has a significant effect on the way our brains develop and function. When children receive sequential music instruction, it can impact their proficiency in language, reading, math and cognition. Our visual arts instruction increases children's awareness of their physical environment, extends and develops the use of the senses and encourages inventive thinking. This year, we will continue to add other art disciplines to our programs in collaboration with a residency program.

shortest_values: The outcomes for this class are
longest_values: "We have established a solid relationship with Studio In a School and are in our eighth year of partnership. Our resident artist works diligently with every student in grades K-5. We have very strong parental involvement which is imperative to the success of the program. Studio offers professional development for classroom teachers and has implemented special projects to ""expand the frame"" linking art with other content areas. We are considered a ""STEAM"" school. Students'artwork has been displayed in such venues as The Asia Society,The Brooklyn Historical Society, Museum of the City of New York, and The Metropolitan Museum of Art. Fifth grade students were assigned a special project to create banners for Studio's 40th Anniversary Gala which were then displayed at the Seagram's Building Plaza in Manhattan. We have been awarded a Cultural After School Adventures grant through our local councilman. Through this grant, permanent artwork will be displayed for all to enjoy. Our Art Exposition is our culminating event and takes place in the middle of June for students, staff, and parents. Students in our chorus, Pre-K, and Kindergarten classes have performed several holiday shows for our student body and parents alike. All classroom teachers have participated in the NaliniKids program which encourages nurturing the whole child including physical, emotional, and character development. We have been awarded a Solar One grant which fosters a ""green"" environment. Six third-grade students participated in Ballet Tech's beginner's program."

"The Arts program at Bronx Theatre High School provides students with a well-rounded exposure to various forms of the arts. Students at Bronx Theatre High School are encouraged early on to work with each other as an ensemble, and this is conveyed through various forms of artistic expression such as performance, set & costume design and visual arts. As students progress through grade levels, they are given numerous opportunities to work with content teachers and Roundabout Theatre Teaching Artists to explore various aspects of the arts including set design, costume design, dance and acting. Students who express interest in dance work with our in-house Dance Company and choreograph performances.  All graduating seniors have the opportunity to ""walk"" on a Roundabout Theatre Broadway stage. Advanced, and dedicated thespians, who earn 10 or more art/theatre credits (including Advanced Placement Studio Art & Photography/Videography) are eligible to sit for the Comprehensive Theatre Regents examination in their senior year - they have an opportunity for an Arts Endorsed Regents upon graduation. Roundabout Theatre Company has been our partnering organization since the opening of the school in 2003 and continues to provide services to our students through in-class residencies and pre/post-show workshops. Studio art and Advanced Placement Studio Art are new offering at the school in which students complete a sequence of coursework and generate a portfolio of various works including Pop Art, Abstract Drip Art and multi-media collage."

The Arts Program at PS/IS 206 includes two certified visual arts teachers, two certified music teachers, one certified drama teacher and one certified dance teacher. In the 2017-18 school year, PS/IS 206 will be adding an additional visual arts teacher to the Arts department. The elementary music program at P.S. 206 is a sequenced program that addresses musical feeling, concepts, music literacy, cultural context, and performance. The middle school program includes General Music building a foundation of music which includes:  the instruments of the orchestra, traditional notation, tablature, Western and World Music History, musical theater and the Little Kids Rock Modern Band Program. Performances are done throughout the school year. The Dance program at P.S./I.S. 206 is a creative based program focused on the Elements of Dance and techniques such as Ballet, Modern, Jazz, Hip-Hop, and cultural dance forms. Through the Blueprint for the Arts in Dance, we study various choreographers, and the history of each dance form. Students are creative choreographers through the art of dance-making including a partnership with Alvin Ailey. The PS 206 theatre program is designed to introduce students to theatre as an art for and means of communication, engage their creativity in developing original performance material, and build their skills as theatre artists and lifelong learners. The Visual Arts Program at is aligned with the NYC Blueprint for Arts and students explore drawing, painting, sculpture paper-mache, printmaking, and collage.

Queens School of Inquiry is a 6-12 Early College Initiative School. All middle school students receive instruction in art,music, and theater. Students learn the basics in drawing, painting, art history and art criticism in 6th and 7th grade. In music, all students gain basic knowledge in reading and composing music and all students learn to play the recorder and violin/viola in 6th and 7th grade. In theater, all 8th grade students take the Introduction to Musical Theatre course. When students enter high school, every freshman student is scheduled for Acting I & II. Opportunities are extended to students who wish to enroll in advanced level drama courses, college art courses and/or high school art/music electives. Outside of the school day, QSI offers MS Musical, art club and SING!. The mission of the Queen's School of Inquiry Arts Department is to foster a passion and dedication for the Visual, Musical, and Theatrical Arts. We want our students to become collaborative creators of culture and change through the various artistic disciplines while exploring their identity. Beginning in 6th grade and continuing until 12th grade, students are exposed to many aspects of the arts including: acting, analysis, criticism, dance, design, directing, music, playwriting, history, research, and visual arts. The QSI Arts Department is expanding in the 2017-2018 school year. Our current 10th grade students will have the ability to receive an advanced arts diploma designated in theater if they fulfill 10 credits in theater related coursework.

Every year, PS 86 strives to improve our arts programming. Our music teacher is a certified music professional who is trained and knowledgeable in instrumental, chorus, and overall in creating musical scores with the students. Our lessons are interdisciplinary and with our ongoing curriculum writing, this enables us to improve our shows and assemblies, while supporting the arts. We currently have two Art teachers who service the students with visual arts in the classroom. The Theatre Arts teacher encompasses the arts, theatre, and literacy.The students are not the only ones learning and growing. Our parent involvement has increased with each passing year through the arts and craft sessions provided by the school. We encourage parents to participate in arts/crafts, tutorials, museum trips, and live day and evening performances. Our annual Art Day is the culminating event preceded by a month long study of a famous artist. Our multicultural fashion show in February, depicts the fashion, art, dance moves, and music of a particular country from around the world. Our music teacher has immersed our students with learning the piano and the guitar for 4th and 5th grades. Our poetry club performs in a poetry performance which includes and culminates in a student-based, student created, movie, filmed and edited by our PE teacher. Our 5th grade chorus performs at The National Choral Festival each year for the past four years. Overall, the students have the opportunity to become inspired while becoming lifelong learners through the arts.

frequent_values: As we have enrolled numerous ENL students in the past few months, we aim to broaden the visual literacy through the arts and music program to engage all learners through a wider, more universal lens.

In spite of budget cutbacks and other obstacles we at PS 157X believe that exposure to the arts is extremely important for all students and at all cost we continue to keep and provide our students with music, art and dance even though sometimes it is quite difficult due to the fact that we are not funded by any CBO and/or Arts Program.  We do this all ourselves because of our belief in our children's need for that exposure.

307 is not a DOE building which sometimes tends to hinder us in programing.  Our gym is the only room available for dance and theater arts.  We now have a certified gym teacher and it is extremely difficult scheduling both the gym program and dance residencies which require gym space.

Our school is a school which heavily relies on grants for the integration of other art forms.  We are underbudgeted and without grants cannot afford to bring in residencies.  Our Salsa Dance/Zumba and theater enrichment groups  programs  take place after school through a CASA grant

This year P.S. 86 art teachers, on one of the extended days, explored techniques used in assessing art in the classroom to further develop students' skill levels, their interpretive sensibilities, their use of materials as well as assessing individual and group progress.

shortest_values: We are a dual language PK-8 school.
longest_values: "The Visual art program at P.S. 138 helps students develop confidence, creativity and literacy througgh creative projects.The curriculum is align with the standards and benchmarks set forth by NYC DOE blueprint for Visual Art.PS 138, art program goal is to make art the starting point with art making.By connecting art to every subject in the school's curriculum, and by interconnecting a multidisciplinary art program, students not only benefit from the structure of each class, but also from their diversity.The art program is intergrating between every subject in other to give student a rich ,well varied, and all-emcompas art education. Throught the expolration of a variety media- drawings, collage, painting, and now theater, Ps 138 is helping students develop an understanding of the principal of art and the elements of design. Students are able to use academic art language to discuss artworks and always cite ""visual evidence"" to support inferences, claim, and arguments made about a work of art. Goal 1: To increase student's awareness of Visual arts. 1)Introcuce different artist, art element, principles of design, and art forms to students.Goal 2: To demonstrade and develop Arts methods that support students achievement. Goal 3:To educate students about art, as well as celebrate students's creativity.This year,PS 138 partner with The New Victory theater to enhance art instruction in the middle school. Our Visual art program strives to give all students a well rounded art experience, and encourage them to create a work of art."

"Our school is committed to providing our students with a rich and diverse arts experience. This experience includes exposure to all arts disciplines, integration of art into the instructional program and exposure to all of our city's art rich cultural institutions and resources. Our students learn to appreciate art in their environment and they understand how art contributes to their lives. Our teachers are also committed to art learning through ongoing professional development offered throughout the year. They integrate visual arts into all subject areas and help students explore their creative talents in a variety of disciplines including visual arts, drama, music, dance and technology. We have great arts partnerships that help us to provide students with rich experience in all of the above. We provide music exposure and learning to all of our early childhood students and we offer instrumental music instruction in woodwinds, percussion and violin to students in third through eighth grade. Our goal moving forward is to grow our art program so that there is cumulative learning in visual arts and music in pre-kindergarten through eighth grade and to integrate theater arts into the middle school curriculum so that there is alignment to content area learning. We also seek additional funds for instruction in  visual arts on every grade.  ""Excellence, Engagement and Enrichment"" is our mission statement and we are committed to offering our students a well rounded arts experience utilizing our school and city resources."

P186X is a District 75/Citywide Special Education school located in the Bronx, southeast of Crotona Park. There are a total of 69 classes throughout the P186X organization. The main site has a total of 46 classes, grades K-8, which consists of: thirteen Standardized Assessment 8:1:1 classes, fourteen Standardized Assessment 12:1:1 classes, six Alternate Assessment 12:1:4 classes, six Alternate Assessment 12:1:1 classes, two Alternate Assessment 8:1:1 classes, and five Alternate Assessment 6:1:1 classes. In addition to the main building there are five annexes which are: P186X@PS306X which consists of 16 Alternate Assessment classes, grades K-8: four 12:1:4 classes, eight 12:1:1 classes, two 12:1:1 bilingual classes (one Transitional Bilingual Education (TBE) and one Dual Language Program (DLP), and two 8:1:1 classes. The P186X@PS140X annex consists of four Standardized Assessment 12:1:1 classes, grades K-5. P186X@New York State Psychiatric Institute has one adolescent High School class. P186X@Bronx Studio High School and P186X@ PS140X each have one inclusion class. Our vision is for all students to be engaged and excel in Science, Technology, Engineering, Arts, and Mathematics (STEAM), academics and social skills to be prepared for college and careers. Our mission is to provide students with the necessary tools to transition into a Least Restrictive Environment (LRE) by providing them with access to learning through representation, action/expression, and engagement.

"P.S. 28 provides students from diverse backgrounds and abilities with a comprehensive arts program. Our goal is to expose students to theater, music, dance and visual arts to support the development of their artistic and creative minds. Music comes alive with students singing and performing in winter, spring and summer concerts. Classroom teachers provide opportunities for students to participate in dance in their classrooms. Puppetry in Practice provides students with an art/theater experience. Pre- kindergarten and Kindergarten students create puppets that come alive to tell a story. Second grade students participate in a Stop Motion Animation residency where they explore ""communities"". First Grade students participate in an art residency with a ""Tiffany"" glass focus showing students a connection between the past and the present. Puppetry in Practice provides parent workshops on how art can be a medium to support literacy. In addition to a full visual arts program, we hold an annual art show where students' work has been showcased at the Queens Borough Arts Festival and the Metropolitan Museum of Art. In addition to our arts residencies and certified arts teachers, classroom teachers provide many opportunities for our young students to use their imagination and creativity to explore the arts in all subject areas."

Our school has a fifteen year relationship with the DreamYard Project. Through year-long residencies, DY artists meet to plan sessions and teach with Marble Hill teacher in a two hour block weekly class.  All 9th and 10th grade students take a DY class of their choice for the year: theater, visual art, dance, film or music production. One of the 10th grade choices for their art class is a film class that is taught by a classroom teacher who was trained by a DY teacher for five years. DY also provides after-school arts opportunities off-site such as Saturday arts classes at their DY Center in the Bronx and Poetry Exchange group that includes elementary, middle and high schools in the Bronx, Japan and South Korea. Additionally DreamYard had included us in an ILearn project with Morocco where students and teachers from schools in Morocco do virtual exchange with our school.  Another long-standing partnership is with Lincoln Center (Open Stages).    Through this program, our entire 10th grade sees 1-2 live theater events each year. This year we also received an Arts for ELL grant from the DOE. We added on two additional dance classes that meet 2 times a week as well as two  digital photography classes that meet once a week. Lastly, we have a NYC Photo elective taught by a Marble Hill teacher.
